## ✅ Lesson 2 — What is API (From Scratch, Real QA Engineer Explanation)

Now we go step-by-step from basics.

You are working on **Philips HPM Support Tool**, so understand API in **real product context**, not textbook.

---

## 🔹 1. What is API (Simple Meaning)

API = Application Programming Interface

Simple meaning:

> API is a way for one software to talk to another software.

In your project:

```
WPF UI → API → Backend → Database
```

UI cannot directly talk to DB or device.
It must go through API.

So API = middle layer

---

## 🔹 2. Real Example from HPM Support Tool

User clicks Login.

What happens internally:

```
UI → API → Backend → DB → Response → UI
```

API example:

```
POST /api/login
```

Request:

```
username = azeez
password = ****
```

Response:

```
token = abc123
role = FSE
```

UI uses response to show screen.

QA must test this API.

---

## 🔹 3. Why API exists (Very important)

Without API:

❌ UI cannot get data
❌ Device cannot send data
❌ Backend cannot send response
❌ Role logic cannot work
❌ Security cannot work

With API:

✅ UI gets data
✅ Device sends data
✅ Role control works
✅ Backend validation works
✅ Secure login works

In medical systems, API controls everything.

---

## 🔹 4. API in Hospital Patient Monitoring System

Real flow:

```
Monitor Device → Backend → API → Support Tool UI
```

Example:

Device sends heart rate

```
Device → API → /vitals → backend → DB → UI
```

Support tool shows device list

```
UI → API → /devices → backend → device service
```

Role check

```
UI → API → /features → backend → role service
```

Enumerator screen

```
UI → API → /enumerator → backend → hardware service
```

So every feature = API.

---

## 🔹 5. Types of API used in Healthcare Products

In Philips / Siemens / GE systems mostly used:

| Type         | Used for                 |
| ------------ | ------------------------ |
| REST API     | Most common              |
| HTTP API     | Web / tool communication |
| Internal API | Service to service       |
| Device API   | Hardware connection      |
| Auth API     | Login / token            |
| Config API   | Settings                 |
| DB API       | Data access              |

You will mostly test:

✅ REST API
✅ HTTP API
✅ Auth API
✅ Role API
✅ Device API

---

## 🔹 6. What QA tests in API

QA does NOT just send request.

QA validates:

✔ Status code
✔ Response body
✔ JSON data
✔ Role permissions
✔ DB data
✔ Error handling
✔ Security
✔ Integration

Example:

```
GET /devices
```

Check:

* Status = 200
* Device list correct
* Role allowed
* DB data correct

This is API testing.

